The bug is in `platform/plugin-sdk/src/fetch.ts` lines 107-113. The `fetchJSONImpl` function has this condition:

```typescript
if (response.status === 204 || response.headers.get('content-length') === '0') {
    if (!schema) {
      return undefined;
    }
    throw ToolError.validation(
      `fetchJSON: expected JSON response from ${url} but received 204 No Content — the server returned no body to validate`,
    );
  }
```

The error message on line 112 hardcodes '204 No Content' regardless of the actual response status. Fix the error message to use the actual status code, e.g.:

```typescript
throw ToolError.validation(
  `fetchJSON: expected JSON response from ${url} but received HTTP ${response.status} with no body to validate`,
);
```

For tests, the test file is `platform/plugin-sdk/src/fetch.test.ts`. The test server already has a `/no-content` endpoint (line 169) that returns 204. Add a new endpoint like `/empty-200` that returns status 200 with `Content-Length: 0` and an empty body. Then add two tests:
1. `fetchJSON with schema on 200 + content-length: 0 throws with actual status code` — verify the error message contains 'HTTP 200' and does NOT contain '204'
2. `fetchJSON without schema on 200 + content-length: 0 returns undefined` — verify backward-compatible behavior

The existing test for 204 + schema (line 616) should still pass since the new message format covers 204 too.
